{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01BXd9LpeFezg3VaJ6iMRWDR","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see - the oracle uses `ray_node_count_from_head` - it actually execs into the head pod to count nodes, not into the client pod. The validation command in the prompt (`kubectl -n ray exec ray-client -- python -c \"import ray; ray.init(address='ray-head:6379'); print('ok'); ray.shutdown()\"`) is the \"human-readable\" check.\n\nBut looking at the validation command more carefully: it does `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')` from inside the ray-client pod. Let me understand why this fails.\n \nThe real problem is that `ray.init(address='gcs_address')` in Ray 2.9.0 isn't just a driver-only operation - it also attempts to start a local raylet. The `_wait_and_get_for_node_address` error is where it's waiting for that local raylet to write its node IP address file, which never happens. Let me check what `ray_node_count_from_head` actually does in the oracle.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2217,"cache_read_input_tokens":40590,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2217},"output_tokens":27,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9fc9f22f-1ad2-4f8c-8c0a-cb7f3b7bd390","uuid":"6a6ccd3f-1d68-4ca1-9deb-37872ddd6f74","request_id":"req_011CcLtNdBfaYTgT9DFdHfaB"}
